  <section class="hero">
   <div class="wrap">
    <h1>
     [ES]: Hands-only CPR for sudden cardiac arrest
    </h1>
    <p>
     [ES]: If an adult or teenager suddenly collapses, is not responding, and is not breathing normally, their heart may have stopped. Calling for help and pushing hard and fast on the chest can help keep blood moving until help arrives. You do not need training or special equipment to try. Free to read, print, and share.
    </p>
   </div>
  </section>
  <main id="main">
   <div class="wrap">
    <p class="lede">
     [ES]: Sudden cardiac arrest is when the heart suddenly stops pumping blood. The person collapses, stops responding, and stops breathing normally (or only gasps). Without blood flow to the brain, every minute counts. Starting CPR right away can improve the chance of survival.
    </p>
    <div class="actions no-print">
     <a class="btn" href="javascript:window.print()">
      [ES]: Print this page
     </a>
     <a class="btn alt" href="cpr-onepager.pdf">
      [ES]: Download printable PDF
     </a>
    </div>
    <div class="box emergency">
     <span class="tag">
      Call emergency services first
     </span>
     <h3>
      [ES]: Collapsed and not breathing normally = emergency
     </h3>
     <p>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: Call your local emergency number (examples: 911, 112, or 999; verify locally) immediately, or tell a specific person to call and to find an AED. Put the phone on speaker so the dispatcher can guide you. Do not wait to be sure — if someone is unresponsive and not breathing normally, start CPR.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [ES]: Three quick checks
    </h2>
    <div class="steps">
     <ol>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [ES]: Check for a response.
       </strong>
       [ES]: Tap their shoulders firmly and shout, “Are you OK?” If they do not respond, they need help now.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [ES]: Check breathing.
       </strong>
       [ES]: Look at the chest for no more than about 10 seconds. If they are not breathing, or are only gasping, struggling, or making occasional noisy breaths, treat it as cardiac arrest.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: Call and get an AED.
       </strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: Call emergency services (speaker phone) and send someone for the nearest automated external defibrillator (AED). If you are alone with a phone, call first, then start CPR.
      </li>
     </ol>
    </div>
    <p>
     [ES]: Gasping — slow, noisy, irregular breaths in the first minutes — is
     <strong>
      [ES]: not
     </strong>
     [ES]: normal breathing. It is a sign of cardiac arrest. Start CPR.
    </p>
    <h2>
     [ES]: How to do hands-only CPR (adults &amp; teens)
    </h2>
    <div class="box warn">
     <span class="tag warn">
      Push hard, push fast, don't stop
     </span>
     <ol>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [ES]: Kneel beside them
       </strong>
       [ES]: on a firm, flat surface. Place the heel of one hand on the
       <strong>
        [ES]: centre of the chest
       </strong>
       [ES]: (on the breastbone, between the nipples). Put your other hand on top and interlock your fingers.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [ES]: Push down hard and fast.
       </strong>
       [ES]: Keep your arms straight and your shoulders directly over your hands, and press straight down at least
       <strong>
        🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: 5 cm (2 inches)
       </strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: deep — about one-third the depth of the chest — but not more than about 6 cm (2.4 inches).
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [ES]: Let the chest come all the way back up
       </strong>
       [ES]: between pushes (full recoil) without lifting your hands off. This lets the heart refill.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: Keep a fast, steady rate of 100–120 pushes per minute
       </strong>
       [ES]: — about two per second. The beat of many well-known upbeat songs works as a guide.
      </li>
      <li>
       <strong>
        [ES]: Do not stop
       </strong>
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: except to use an AED or to swap with someone. Switch with another bystander about every 2 minutes if you can, to keep pushes strong — good compressions are tiring.
      </li>
     </ol>
    </div>
    <p>
     [ES]: For an untrained rescuer helping an adult or teen,
     <strong>
      [ES]: hands-only CPR
     </strong>
     [ES]: — continuous chest compressions with no rescue breaths — is recommended and effective. If you are trained and willing, give 30 compressions then 2 rescue breaths, but never let giving breaths delay or interrupt good chest compressions for long.
    </p>
    <h2>
     🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: Use an AED as soon as one arrives
    </h2>
    <div class="box ok">
     <span class="tag ok">
      AEDs are made for untrained bystanders
     </span>
     <p>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: An AED is a small device, often found in airports, schools, gyms, offices, and shopping centres.
      <strong>
       [ES]: Turn it on and follow the spoken instructions
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: — it tells you exactly what to do. Stick the pads on the person's bare chest as shown in the pictures on the pads. Keep doing chest compressions while the pads go on. When the AED says “analysing,” make sure no one is touching the person. If it advises a shock, make sure everyone is clear, then press the button. Right after any shock or any “no shock” message,
      <strong>
       [ES]: resume compressions immediately
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: and keep following the AED.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [ES]: When to stop
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      [ES]: Emergency responders or another trained person takes over.
     </li>
     <li>
      [ES]: The person clearly wakes up, moves, opens their eyes, and starts to breathe normally. If so, roll them onto their side (recovery position) and keep watching their breathing.
     </li>
     <li>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: An AED instructs you to stop while it analyses or delivers a shock (resume immediately afterward).
     </li>
     <li>
      [ES]: You are too exhausted to continue and no one can take over.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <h2>
     [ES]: Children, babies, drowning, and overdose
    </h2>
    <div class="box warn">
     <span class="tag warn">
      Breaths matter more here
     </span>
     <p>
      [ES]: In babies and children, and when collapse is caused by drowning, choking, or a drug overdose, lack of oxygen is usually the cause, so
      <strong>
       [ES]: rescue breaths are especially valuable
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: . If you are trained, give breaths with compressions (commonly 30 compressions to 2 breaths; trained child/infant responders often use 15:2 with two rescuers). For a baby, use two fingers in the centre of the chest and push about 4 cm (1.5 inches) deep. If you are not trained, the dispatcher can guide you — and doing chest compressions alone is far better than doing nothing.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [ES]: Good to know
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [ES]: Do not wait because you are worried about being perfect.
      </strong>
      [ES]: The biggest mistake is doing nothing. A person in cardiac arrest needs immediate help.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [ES]: Cracked ribs can happen
      </strong>
      [ES]: and are not a reason to stop if the person is in cardiac arrest — effective compressions can save a life.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [ES]: Don't check for a pulse
      </strong>
      [ES]: if you are untrained — it wastes time and is easy to get wrong. Go by responsiveness and breathing.
     </li>
     <li>
      [ES]: A heart attack (a blocked artery, often with chest pain) is different from cardiac arrest, but a heart attack can lead to cardiac arrest — so if someone with chest pain collapses and stops breathing normally, start CPR.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [ES]: Learn CPR in person
      </strong>
      [ES]: if you can. Short, low-cost or free classes are widely available and build the confidence to act.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <h2>
     [ES]: Sources
    </h2>
    <ul class="sources">
     <li>
      <a href="https://cpr.heart.org/en/cpr-courses-and-kits/hands-only-cpr">
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: American Heart Association (AHA) — Hands-Only CPR
      </a>
      [ES]: and
      <a href="https://cpr.heart.org/en/resuscitation-science/first-aid-guidelines/first-aid">
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: AHA CPR &amp; first-aid guidelines
      </a>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: (compression rate 100–120/min, depth at least 2 in / 5 cm, full recoil, minimise interruptions).
     </li>
     <li>
      <a href="https://www.redcross.org/take-a-class">
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: American Red Cross — CPR/AED training and resources
      </a>
      [ES]: for adults, children, and infants.
     </li>
     <li>
      <a href="https://www.resus.org.uk/library">
       [ES]: Resuscitation Council UK — resuscitation and basic life support guidance library
      </a>
      [ES]: (adult and paediatric).
     </li>
     <li>
      <a href="https://cprguidelines.eu/">
       🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: European Resuscitation Council (ERC) — CPR guidelines
      </a>
      .
     </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="sources">
     [ES]: Steps reflect widely taught basic-life-support sequences for lay responders. Training bodies differ in small details — follow your local first-aid training and your emergency dispatcher's instructions.
    </p>
    <p class="disclaimer">
     🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [ES]: This guide is general information, not medical advice, and is not a substitute for hands-on CPR and AED training, which is widely available and strongly recommended. In an emergency, always call your local emergency number. Reuse and reprint freely.
    </p>
   </div>
